    <title>Combined summary - Bitcoind-in-background mode for SPV wallets</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T19:24:53.397034+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-April/005147.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In April 2014, Bitcoin developers engaged in discussions aimed at improving the efficiency and usability of the network while addressing the decline in the number of full nodes supporting it. Suggestions included integrating IPv6 tunneling and teredo into Bitcoind to make instances IPv6-reachable automatically, exposing existing instances to the internet, bundling ipv6 tunnelling into bitcoind, and optimizing NAT tunneling code. The broken incentive model of the network's security was also discussed, and some members suggested that economics should work for rather than against the network. Suggestions were made to improve payment channel implementations, extend addr broadcasts, optimize NAT tunneling code, and create separate 'node control' user interfaces instead of packaging them with wallets. Discussions also touched on the issue of a broken incentive model and the need for education and improvement in implementation warts rather than significant changes to the design of the network.Another thread of email exchanges focused on ways to increase security for users while using Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) wallets. It was suggested that an option could be added to popular SPV wallets to spin a bitcoind process in the background to provide a local trusted node. Additionally, it was suggested that the core could accommodate this 'embedded' usage by providing specific interfaces, special builds, bindings, DLLs, etc. The goal was to ensure that serious users of Bitcoin run a bitcoind as a border router and connect SPV wallets with higher functionality to that trusted node(s) to ensure they are all on the same trunk of the chain. The team also discussed the importance of serving headers by default but storing and serving full blocks configurable to ranges and reducing the memory or disk footprint of the core to make it as low as an optimal storage of UTXO.There were concerns about the decrease in the number of full nodes due to other wallets getting ahead in features and usability. Bloom filters and Tor were discussed in terms of privacy implications, and the importance of instrumentation in SPV wallets was emphasized to report back to home base how long they are running for, how much disk space and RAM they have, and what kind of hardware. Suggestions were made to support Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) clients through bundling Stratum with Bitcoind, indicating block availability, and implementing error correction in the Bitcoin network. The use of error coding can provide an anti-censorship effect, and discussions touched on ways to obtain transaction data without scanning the blockchain.In addition to technical considerations, the email threads also addressed issues of privacy and security. Some members encouraged the use of email encryption for online privacy, while others highlighted the importance of using full nodes for increased security. Developers discussed the potential drawbacks of using bloom filters for privacy and incentivizing people to commit resources to the network through instant machine-to-machine micro payments. Another thread of email exchanges focused on the development of Bitcoin's performance on desktops and the incompatibility between wallets and nodes. Suggestions included creating a separate 'node control' user interface to encourage people to run a node when their wallet is not running, using machine-to-machine micro payments as an incentive, and using pruning to support a full node in approximately 4GB or so. However, practical consequences need to be addressed, such as needing bitcoins to pay a node for serving and the potential overload of free nodes if some nodes charge while others don't. The conversation also touched on the hub/spoke concept and error correction in the network.Overall, the email conversations demonstrate ongoing efforts to improve the Bitcoin network and address its challenges by finding ways to optimize the implementation and efficiency of the Bitcoin protocol.</summary>
